## Deferred — ComBus typed/pluggable groups + dual-frame (2026-04-17)

### Context
The current AnalogComBusID / DigitalComBusID enums use range markers (MOTION_END,
LIGHT_END…) to partition channels into logical groups within a single flat array.
This is zero-cost and sufficient for the current UART transport.

### Deferred idea 1 — typed channel groups (pluggable sub-bus)
Instead of a single flat enum, each logical group becomes its own typed struct
carrying its own array pointer:
    MotionComBus    motion;    // STEERING, RPM, DUMP, ESC_SPEED
    LightComBus     light;     // LIGHTS_STATE, ...
    CoreComBus      core;      // HORN, KEY, BATTERY_LOW
Modules include only the sub-bus they need. A ComBus node connects its sub-bus
via pointer — not included = not transmitted. Benefit: true optional groups,
no guard macros, no dead frame slots. Cost: protocol change (separate frame per
group or muxing scheme needed), heavier refactor.
Prerequisite: a use case with ≥3 independent modules having genuinely disjoint
channel needs AND a transport that can carry multiple frame types.

### Deferred idea 2 — dual-frame (high-rate control + low-rate config)
Inspired by CANopen PDO/SDO. A high-rate frame carries time-critical controls
(sticks, on/off signals). A low-rate frame carries slow config (brightness
potentiometer, PID trims, EEPROM settings from remote).
Current transport handles both at 200 Hz — acceptable since all channels are
small (uint16_t). Becomes relevant when a remote brightness pot needs to reach
the light node without consuming bandwidth in every control frame.
Simplest implementation: Nth-frame mux — every N frames, certain channels carry
config data. No protocol change needed, just a frame counter in combus_tx.
Prerequisite: a confirmed use case (e.g. brightness pot on remote → light node)
before adding complexity.


