## Deferred — Shaker motor architecture (2026-04-25)

### Context
The shaker is currently a standalone `DcMotorCore` instance (`s_shakerDev` in
`hw_init_dcdev.cpp`), driven every loop iteration by `shaker_hw_update()`.
Speed is computed directly from `comBus.analogBus[ENGINE_RPM_BUS].value` and
`gMixerState.engineOn` — no intermediate bus struct.

### Deferred idea 1 — shaker as a dcdev slot (winter 2026)
Integrate the shaker into the existing `dcDevObj[]` array alongside the other DC
outputs, using the same module-pointer attachment pattern:
- Add a `Shaker` entry to the `DcPort` enum in `sound_board_esp32.h`.
- Remove the standalone `s_shakerDev`, `shaker_hw_init()` and `shaker_hw_update()`.
- `dc_init()` instantiates the Shaker slot like any other DC channel.
- The compute step (RPM → speed mapping) moves into a vehicle-profile `SoundUpdateFn`,
  keeping `main.cpp` free of vehicle-specific logic.
Prerequisite: `dc_update()` infrastructure + sound profile loop decoupled from `main.cpp`.

### Deferred idea 2 — cross-node shaker (winter 2026, ComBus v2)
In the target architecture, the machine node computes the shaker speed and sends
it over a `GlobalSoundBus` ComBus channel.  The sound node reads that channel and
drives the motor directly — no local computation.

    Machine node → [GlobalSoundBus: SHAKER_SPEED] → Sound node → DcMotorCore

This requires ComBus v2 (typed channel groups, see "Deferred — ComBus typed/pluggable
groups" above) and the machine/sound architecture merge.
Prerequisite: ComBus v2 + architecture merge (winter 2026). Do not start while the
rc_engine_sound backend is still in place.